**20. ARGUMENTS** Explain why [f(t) = \frac{c}{1 + 60e^{-0.5t}}] approaches but never reaches [c]:
As [t \to \infty], [e^{-0.5t} \to 0], so [f(t) \to \frac{c}{1 + 0} = c]. Since the exponential term is always positive, the denominator is always greater than 1, so [f(t) < c] for all finite [t].

**21. WRITE** Compare how exponential and continuous exponential functions model real-world situations:
* Discrete exponential [y = ab^t] models situations with fixed time periods (annual growth, compound interest periods).
* Continuous exponential [y = ae^{kt}] models situations where growth/decay happens continuously (radioactive decay, heat transfer, continuously compounded interest).

